/* Wing-assisted incline running (WAIR) article? */   proposed solution
A new paper offers evidence to suggest the crest protected the neck from dromaeosaurs.
There is no consensus as to the function of the crest. There is at best a "prevailing view" among controversial explanations.
Use of the crest for neck protection has not been refuted for dromaeosaurs.

I divided jaw muscle attachment into a separate sentence from neck protection. Fragility of the frill would preclude protection from large theropods. Neck protection from droaeosaurs is theoretical but not implausible.
new explanation for the function of the frill and rear-facing spikes
new explanation for the function of the frill
response to deletions of dismount theory
This whole article is theoretical and should include the latest published theory, as peer reviewed by Ken Carpenter and Peter Larson. It is clearly labeled as new, controversial, and hypothetical.
Two references support this this edit. Fraser 2014 was peer reviewed by professionals Ken Carpenter and Peter Larson. Specific constructive feedback welcome.

Hu et al (2009) described short feathers on pedal phalanges and made no comment on running speed. Hu (2009) and Godefroit (2013) noted a complex origin of flight, which can be explained by the dismount theory.
I have added a new model for the origin of avian flight
